The boundary and beginning conditions were double-checked to ensure that they were correctly entered, and physical conservation rules were examined to ensure that they were satisfied in order to validate the consistency of the numerical mistakes and solve the correct mathematical model. Furthermore, linearization and discretization errors were examined to ensure that they were below acceptable limits. It is important to stress that in order to study the mesh independence analysis of simulation, various mesh numbers (84395, 91827, 98946, and 107581) were explored. Fig. 9
                            depicts the mesh independence analysis, which shows that as the mesh number increases from 84,395 to 98946, the temperature rises from 17 °C to 19.5 °C. Indeed, there was no discernible difference in temperature after the mesh number of 98946. In other words, the temperature changes after mesh number 98946; at mesh number 1075, it approximately remained constant at 19.6 °C. Hence, we chose the mesh number 98,946 as an optimum in this study to simulate set-up because of its cost-effectiveness and acceptable results. Experimental results of heater power consumption in an actual and large-scale line heater were compared with CFD data to validate the suggested model (Fig. 10
                           ). The inclusion of synthetic C-dots improved the thermophysical properties of water in the fluid bath, and it is envisaged that the heater's heating performance will be improved and the heater's power consumption to attain a certain gas temperature will be reduced as a result. The introduction of 0.5 and 5 wt% C-dots/DW nanofluids in the line heater reduced the heater's power usage and increasing the NP content resulted in even more power savings. The addition of C-dots to the bath fluid resulted in a decrease in heater power consumption according to CFD studies. The thermophysical properties of nanofluids increase when they behave as single-phase fluids rather than solid–liquid mixtures with micron and nanometer particles distributed. The thermal performance of nanofluids is affected by several characteristics, which enhance their thermal efficiency in heating devices. To have a comprehensive understanding of their behavior in heating and cooling devices, parameters such as gravity, Brownian movement, the friction force between the fluid and NPs, Brownian diffusion, sedimentation, homogeneity of the nanofluids, and thermophysical properties of nanofluids should be taken into account. Even though the particles in the solution are very minute, the slip velocity between them and the fluid cannot be regarded as zero the energy transfer in the solution increases when random and chaotic movements of scattered NPs in the nanofluid take place. The dispersion of NPs in nanofluids helps to maintain temperature uniformity across the system and between the fluid and the walls. The higher thermal performance of nanofluids is attributable to two factors: the nanofluid's improved thermal conductivity and the chaotic mobility of NPs in the nanofluid, which both speed up energy transfer in the solution [68]. The purpose of this research is to see how the thermal conductivity of nanofluids affects the system's thermal performance. As a result, the bath fluids were classified as single-phase nanofluids. As a result, numerical results should not be relied upon to predict experimental outcomes precisely. To put it another way, the effects of modifying the bath fluid's thermophysical properties on the heater's thermal performance and power consumption were studied. As a result, using the created nanofluid samples in a real line heater should lower the heater's energy, fuel, and power consumption, as well as its operational expenses. It is to be noted that the maximum differences between numerical and actual results were 1.9 % related to 5 wt% of c-dots NPs which is not notable. Indeed, it can be explained by the error of solving of numerical section and experimental apparatus. Therefore, it can be concluded that the numerical results have good accuracy and are reliable. From the experimental and numerical results, the greatest heater power consumption reductions were 9.7 % and 10.3 %, respectively.
